01:28.722 --> 01:32.426
* Oh, did you see them?

01:32.460 --> 01:35.596
* They're just walking around,
yeah *

01:47.175 --> 01:50.844
Page: We're in India's largest
city Mumbai, formally Bombay,

01:50.878 --> 01:52.746
to understand what it's like

01:52.780 --> 01:55.816
for the LGBTQ community
in contemporary India.

01:55.849 --> 02:00.454
We've been invited
to the Godrej Culture lab,

02:00.488 --> 02:02.356
an experimental idea space

02:02.390 --> 02:05.459
inside one
of India's largest conglomerates

02:05.493 --> 02:08.696
to meet one of its innovators,
Parmesh Shahani.

02:08.729 --> 02:10.364
-Yes.
-Hi.

02:10.398 --> 02:13.201
Page: He wrote the book
on being gay in Bombay.

02:13.234 --> 02:14.768
It's called "Gay Bombay."

02:14.802 --> 02:17.171
-Welcome to Godrej.
-Thank you.

02:17.205 --> 02:18.506
I'm going to give you
a big adventure.

02:18.539 --> 02:19.707
We have to hold hands together.
-Wow.

02:19.740 --> 02:21.309
That's cool.

02:21.342 --> 02:23.244
That is how you start out
an interview?

02:23.277 --> 02:24.412
Yep.
Welcome to India.

02:24.445 --> 02:27.181
-Thank you.
-[ Chuckles ]

02:27.215 --> 02:30.184
Quite the setup.

02:30.218 --> 02:32.286
We clearly know about
your book, "Gay Bombay,"

02:32.320 --> 02:33.587
and that you are an expert

02:33.621 --> 02:34.855
in your country
on queer culture.

02:34.888 --> 02:36.424
-Yeah.
-And from your point of view,

02:36.457 --> 02:38.326
what are some of the questions
we should be asking?

02:38.359 --> 02:40.261
What are some of things
we should be thinking about?

02:40.294 --> 02:42.830
Sure.
I think the first thing

02:42.863 --> 02:46.434
that you should think about
as you go on India Gaycation

02:46.467 --> 02:51.272
is that in India, the trajectory
of being LGBT is not --

02:51.305 --> 02:52.673
it's not linear at all,

02:52.706 --> 02:55.409
but there are deep
historical narratives.

02:55.443 --> 02:57.611
We have are own
LGBT mythologies.

02:57.645 --> 02:58.912
So to understand that --

02:58.946 --> 03:00.781
what's happening
on the LGBT scene today

03:00.814 --> 03:03.484
is an interplay both
between our history,

03:03.517 --> 03:06.554
our mythology
and of our presence

03:06.587 --> 03:08.789
in a very globalized
LGBT environment.

03:08.822 --> 03:13.761
Um, but I think being queer here
is really about community.

03:13.794 --> 03:16.364
You are not queer alone.

03:16.397 --> 03:17.965
You know, you're queer
in your family,

03:17.998 --> 03:19.800
you're queer with your friends,
you're queer at work.

03:19.833 --> 03:22.836
Every decision you take
is not about self.

03:22.870 --> 03:25.839
Maybe you can also speak
to the impact of colonialism

03:25.873 --> 03:27.808
and sort of what
that has meant

03:27.841 --> 03:29.877
for the community
in this country.

03:29.910 --> 03:31.945
Sure. Sure.
So, pre-colonial India

03:31.979 --> 03:34.248
had a range of possibilities,

03:34.282 --> 03:37.418
and you can see it
if you look at our text.

03:37.451 --> 03:38.986
The colonial project was about,

03:39.019 --> 03:41.355
you know, simplifying
and classifying.

03:41.389 --> 03:46.760
The British gave us Section 377,
which is very problematic.

03:46.794 --> 03:48.996
And I think the reason
why this law stays

03:49.029 --> 03:51.999
and why there is so much
discrimination in society itself

03:52.032 --> 03:54.335
is because of nationalism.

03:54.368 --> 03:57.805
It's because in this imagination
of India post-independence,

03:57.838 --> 04:00.674
LGBT diversity is something
that was ignored.

04:00.708 --> 04:04.044
And I think a lot of people
absorbed colonial, in hangover,

04:04.077 --> 04:06.814
kind of their colonial values
and mind-sets.

04:06.847 --> 04:11.585
Page: Section 377 is a
19th-century British imposed law

04:11.619 --> 04:16.624
that criminalizes intercourse
"against the order of nature,"

04:16.657 --> 04:20.761
which has been interpreted
to persecute homosexuals.

04:20.794 --> 04:24.865
Though it was lifted
for consenting adults in 2009,

04:24.898 --> 04:28.001
it was fully reinstated in 2014.

04:28.035 --> 04:32.806
And so the fight for LGBTQ
rights in India continues.

04:32.840 --> 04:34.742
We can't go back in the closet.

04:34.775 --> 04:38.045
There isn't any such closet now
that I can go back to.

04:40.814 --> 04:42.516
Daniel:
This law, Article 377,

04:42.550 --> 04:44.818
what power does
it actually have?

04:44.852 --> 04:46.720
The fact that this law exists

04:46.754 --> 04:49.823
means that any man who's LGBT
is always afraid.

04:49.857 --> 04:52.660
It's often used
as a form of threat.

04:52.693 --> 04:56.664
It's often used as an excuse
to not give people rights.

04:56.697 --> 04:58.966
It's just something
which is fundamental

04:58.999 --> 05:02.069
to our being recognized as
citizens in our own country.

05:02.102 --> 05:04.372
-Right.
-It's a very base argument.

05:04.405 --> 05:05.839
We just don't want
to be criminal.

05:05.873 --> 05:07.775
But in 2009, when that
was repealed, right?

05:07.808 --> 05:09.810
Yeah.
People were coming out
of the closet.

05:09.843 --> 05:11.945
There was a real celebration,
and I would assume,

05:11.979 --> 05:14.114
some sort of feeling
of liberation that happened.

05:14.147 --> 05:15.749
The High Court thing came,

05:15.783 --> 05:17.951
we had all these
celebratory marches,

05:17.985 --> 05:19.453
and then suddenly,
this thing comes

05:19.487 --> 05:20.954
as one big slap
to everyone's face.

05:20.988 --> 05:22.790
And then what do you do?
I mean, you're all out, right?

05:22.823 --> 05:24.525
It made everyone realize

05:24.558 --> 05:28.061
that a journey towards equality
is not a linear journey.

05:28.095 --> 05:30.531
It's not that we will have
progress, progress, progress.

05:30.564 --> 05:32.366
Thee will be setbacks, right?

05:32.400 --> 05:35.669
So I think the Supreme Court
reversal, while very wrong,

05:35.703 --> 05:39.507
has actually galvanized
the community to act together,

05:39.540 --> 05:41.008
to strategize better.

05:41.041 --> 05:42.810
And over the long term,

05:42.843 --> 05:45.446
I think it will lay the
foundations for a better future.

05:45.479 --> 05:46.614
Right.

05:46.647 --> 05:47.881
Walk and talk?
-Walk and talk.

05:47.915 --> 05:50.684
-Yeah.
-This building is beautiful.

05:50.718 --> 05:51.885
-Yeah.
-Wow. Okay.

05:51.919 --> 05:53.654
-Oh, is that a swing?
-Yeah.

05:53.687 --> 05:55.756
-You want to swing?
-Can I sit on it?

05:55.789 --> 05:58.426
Yeah.
You can fit how many people
on this?

05:58.459 --> 05:59.927
-Three.
-Three, all right.

05:59.960 --> 06:01.862
-I don't trust that.
-All right.

06:01.895 --> 06:03.096
This is fine.

06:03.130 --> 06:04.532
So, what do you do for fun?

06:04.565 --> 06:05.999
Me? Well...
[ Chuckles ]

06:06.033 --> 06:08.035
Like, in a gay way,
and also in a non-gay way.

06:08.068 --> 06:09.770
So where do you hang out?

06:09.803 --> 06:10.938
So gays hang mostly
on Grindr.

06:10.971 --> 06:12.540
We should put you down.

06:12.573 --> 06:14.842
I'm sure yours
is a sight to behold.

06:14.875 --> 06:17.110
So wait, there's this law, but
it's like actually really easy

06:17.144 --> 06:19.112
to get on Grindr
and like...like that?

06:19.146 --> 06:20.814
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Of course.

06:22.182 --> 06:26.654
Page: Well, it sounds like there
still is a network for gay men.

06:26.687 --> 06:29.990
So, as the sun sets
over the city, we wonder,

06:30.023 --> 06:32.460
what's the gay night life like?

06:32.493 --> 06:35.062
[ Dance music plays ]

06:45.806 --> 06:48.976
Daniel: So, there's a party
for the gay community in Mumbai.

06:49.009 --> 06:52.145
I left Ellen at the hotel, and
I'm going to go in by myself

06:52.179 --> 06:54.915
and see what's going on
and check out the scene.

06:54.948 --> 06:57.184
[ Music continues ]

07:07.194 --> 07:09.630
So, wait, what the hell's
going on in there?

07:09.663 --> 07:12.065
**

07:12.099 --> 07:14.602
Man: It's a gay party,
which is hosted by gay Bombay.

07:14.635 --> 07:16.504
People who are out there
inside dancing,

07:16.537 --> 07:17.838
all of them are not out.

07:17.871 --> 07:18.872
Hence, they need
that safe space.

07:18.906 --> 07:20.107
Got it.

07:20.140 --> 07:21.141
And because they need
that safe place,

07:21.174 --> 07:22.710
they come to "G" parties

07:22.743 --> 07:24.077
because they want the parties
completely safe.

07:24.111 --> 07:26.213
Do you know, like, I do have
straight friends,

07:26.246 --> 07:28.081
and I do go clubbing with them,

07:28.115 --> 07:30.484
but I can't do my,
like, belly dance

07:30.518 --> 07:31.852
or something over there.

07:31.885 --> 07:33.487
